  "@type": "Article",
  "dateModified": "2025-12-31",
  "datePublished": "2025-12-31",
  "description": "Federation is a model of networked communication in which independent servers exchange data with one another according to shared protocols, without any single server having authority over the whole network. Each server (often called an instance) operates autonomously — it sets its own policies, manages its own users, and stores its own data — but participates in a larger network by sending and receiving standardized messages.\nIn the context of the fediverse, federation is implemented primarily through the ActivityPub protocol. When a user on one instance follows a user on another, the two servers establish a relationship: the remote server sends new posts to the local server, which displays them to the follower. Replies, likes, and boosts flow back through the same channel.\n",
